The result of the visualization above.¶

  • From the above chart, it shows that there are 12 people within the age range of 25 to 30 that are into Cassava farming. There is only one person within the age range of 20 to 25 that is into Cassava farming. There are six people within the age range of 35 to 40 that are into cassava farming, then none within the age range of 45 and above that is into cassava farming.
  • Note: similar interpretation should be giving to other crops.

# Initializing the LogisticRegression Model
logistic_model = LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000, multi_class='multinomial', solver='newton-cg')

# Training the logisticRegression model
logistic_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Making Prediction
logistic_model_preds=logistic_model.predict(X_test)

# Binarise the labels
y_test_binarized = label_binarize(y_test, classes=np.unique(y_test))

# using OneVsRestClassifier to calculate the ROC-AUC score
ovr=OneVsRestClassifier(LogisticRegression(solver='lbfgs', max_iter=1000))
y_pred_proba_lg=ovr.fit(X_train, y_train).predict_proba(X_test)

# Using metrics to evaluate the trained model
logistic_model_accuracy=accuracy_score(y_test, logistic_model_preds)
logistic_model_precision=precision_score(y_test, logistic_model_preds, average='weighted')
logistic_model_recall=recall_score(y_test, logistic_model_preds, average='weighted')
logistic_model_f1=f1_score(y_test, logistic_model_preds, average='weighted')
logistic_model_auc=roc_auc_score(y_test_binarized, y_pred_proba_lg)

# Display the various scores of the model
print(f"Results for Logistic Regression:")
print(f" Logistic Regression Model Accuracy: {round(logistic_model_accuracy*100, 2)}%")
print(f" Logistic Regression Model Precision: {round(logistic_model_precision*100, 2)}%")
print(f" Logistic Regression Model Recall: {round(logistic_model_recall*100, 2)}%")
print(f" Logistic Regression Model F1: {round(logistic_model_f1*100, 2)}%")
print(f" Logistic Regression Model AUC: {round(logistic_model_auc*100, 2)}%")


# Plot the ROC curve and calculate the AUC score for each class
for i, class_name in enumerate(np.unique(y_test)):
    fpr, tpr, _=roc_curve(y_test_binarized[:,i], y_pred_proba_lg[:, i])
    roc_auc=auc(fpr, tpr)
    sns.lineplot(x=fpr, y=tpr, label=f'ROC curve of class {class_name} (AUC={roc_auc:.2f})')
    sns.lineplot(x=[0, 1], y=[0, 1], color='k', linestyle='--')
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('ROC Curve for Multi-Class Logistic Regression')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Generating the confusion matrix
# using seaborn heatmap
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, logistic_model_preds, labels=['Apples', 'Carrots', 'Lettuce', 'Strawberries', 'Tomatoes'])
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, cbar=False)
plt.xlabel('Predicted Values')
plt.ylabel('Actual Values')
plt.title('Confusion Matrix of the Logistic Regression')
plt.show()
